Peter:

You can set the variables as strings in the following format in python: 

gas.set(T=900.0,P=1.0e5,X=&#39;CH4:&#39;+str(mole_CH4)+&#39;,O2:&#39;+str(mole_O2)+&#39;,N2:&#39;+str(mole_N2)+&#39;&#39;)

-Gokul-

Peter Perez &lt;plpd00@...&gt; wrote:                             Thanks Anatoli and Dave for your kind reply. What I meant (not sure 
 what a &quot;functor&quot; is) is to be able to set the mole fractions by using 
 variables instead of the string in the set command. For example, I 
 would like to do something like this:

 mole_CH4 = 1.0
 mole_O2 = 1/phi*(1+y/4.0))  # phi and y are computed in my code.
 mole_N2 = (1/phi*(1+y/4.0)*(Xn2/Xo2))  # Xn2, Xo2 are mole fractions.

 Then set the mole fractions with something like this:
 gas.set(T=900.0,P=1.0e5,X=&#39;CH4:mole_CH4,O2:mole_O2,N2:mole_N2&#39;)

 Right now, I just compute the new stoichiometry (according to my phi) 
 and then modify the value in the set command. This is not a big deal, 
 but it takes some time when you want to do the calculation for many 
 conditions. Anatoli&#39;s approach is a very good idea. However, it still 
 requires the mole fractions to be given as strings, which do not 
 support arithmetic operations. Thank you both again for your interest 
 and help. Best Regards, Peter

